data.title: Fed Chair Powell hints against DEC rate cut due to differing views and data gaps amid gov shutdown. Rate hike probability now at 12% from 1%.
data.description: Fed Chair Jerome Powell stated that another interest rate cut in December is not guaranteed, as the Federal Open Market Committee is divided and facing data gaps. The Fed recently lowered rates to 3.75%-4.00%, leading to market expectations of a third cut due to slowing growth. However, Powell's comments caused a reevaluation, with the probability of holding rates steady rising to 12%, up from 1%. The committee is divided on how to proceed, with some focused on upside inflation risks and others on labor market softness. The U.S. government shutdown is limiting key statistics, complicating the Fed's decision-making process.

data.title: Fed cuts rates by 0.25%, halts balance sheet runoff. Balance sheet now at $6.59 trillion from $9 trillion peak.
data.description: The Federal Reserve made a significant decision by reducing its benchmark interest rate by 25 basis points, now set within a range of 3.75% to 4.00%. In addition, they announced a cessation to the runoff of their security holdings beginning in December. The Federal Open Market Committee stated during the Wednesday meeting that they would halt the reduction of their holdings of Treasury and agency mortgage-backed securities as of December 1, which signifies the conclusion of the quantitative tightening program that initiated in mid-2022. Prior to this decision, the Fed's balance sheet had peaked near $9 trillion but had decreased to $6.59 trillion. The Committee mentioned that they opted to finalize the reduction of their aggregate holdings, detailing the plan in a comprehensive piece on Benzinga.com.
